# Backend Standards (Node.js)

## Error Handling

- Never silently catch exceptions — always log and re-throw or return error response
- Structured logging (Winston / Pino) with context: `logger.error('msg', { error, userId })`
- Custom error classes for domain errors: `DatabaseError`, `ValidationError`, etc.

## External Services — Fail Fast

Never silently swallow failures from email, SMS, or payment providers.

```typescript
// ❌ silent skip — caller doesn't know email wasn't sent
if (!apiKey) { console.log('No key, skipping'); return; }

// ✅ throw so caller can handle it
if (!apiKey) throw new Error('Email provider not configured');
```

In dev without keys: log OTP/token to console explicitly. In production: always throw.

## Input Validation

- Validate with schema (Zod / Joi) in middleware BEFORE route handler
- Sanitize all inputs before DB writes

## Auth & Security

- JWT validation on all protected routes
- Rate limit public endpoints
- Env vars for all config — fail on startup if required vars are missing

## Deployment

- Multi-stage Dockerfile: builder stage (devDeps + `tsc`) → final stage (prod deps only)
- `CMD`: `node dist/index.js` — never `npm run dev`
- Backend reads `PORT` from env (Railway sets it automatically)

## Practices

- async/await over callbacks
- Database connection pooling
- Graceful shutdown handlers (`SIGTERM`, `SIGINT`)
